Picardie, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"1210–1282":"1210–1282","1150–Female":"1150–Deceased","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1215–1293":"1215–1293","1234–Male":"1234–Deceased","1235–1283":"1235–1283","1205–Male":"1205–Deceased","1235–1296":"1235–1296","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1190–Female":"1190–Deceased","1190":"1190","28 July 1251":"28 July 1251","1296":"1296","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1283":"1283","1282":"1282","1293":"1293","1150":"1150","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1234":"1234","1210":"1210","about 1210":"about 1210","Perruel, Eure, Normandie, France":"Perruel, Eure, Normandy, France","Beauvais, Oise, Picardie, France":"Beauvais, Oise, Picardie, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Crépin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Huguenot: relationship name: French  <b>Crépin</b>, from the Old French personal name  <i>Crespin</i> (  compare  Crispin  ). The name may sometimes have been absorbed by English   Crippin  , particularly in Kent."],"variants":[{"name":"Crippin","meanings":["English: variant of   Crispin  .","Irish: variant of   Gribbin  ."]},{"name":"Crispin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Pedro, Alicia, Fernando, Manuel, Rafael, Adolfo, Alfredo, Ana, Areli, Candita.  French Adrien, Andre, Eugenie, Francoise.","English; Spanish (<b>Crispín</b>): from the personal name Middle English <i>Crispin</i>, Spanish <i>Crispín</i>, from Latin <i>Crispinus</i>, derived from <i>crispus</i> ‘curly-haired’ (see   Crisp  ). This name was especially popular in France in the early Middle Ages, having been borne by a Christian saint who was martyred at Soissons in  AD <i>c.</i> 285 along with a companion, <i>Crispinianus</i> (whose name is a further derivative of the same word). Compare   Crespin   and 3 below.","English (of Norman origin): from Old French and Middle English <i>crespin</i>, <i>crispin</i> ‘curly-haired’, also found as <i>Crepin</i>; see   Crippin  . It is difficult to tell this apart from the personal name in 1 above. According to Lanfranc, archbishop of Canterbury (1070–1089), the Norman Gilbert Crispin was the first man to receive this nickname, and two of his sons adopted it as their surname. His grandson Gilbert Crispin became abbot of Westminster in 1085. Members of the Norman family were said to have inherited a shock of hair that stood up stiffly like a bristly pine, as though the name derived from Latin <i>crispus pinus</i>, but this derivation is a medieval invention."]}]},{"name":"Léonore","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Eléonore .   See  <b>Leonora</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Leonora","meanings":["Shortened form of   Eleonora ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Léonore Crépin was born in 1210, her father, Guillaume IV du Bec-Crespin, was 26 and her mother, Amicie de ROYE, was 21. She had at least 1 son with Guillaume de Beauvais II. She died in 1282, in Perruel, Eure, Normandy, France, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1210–1282":"1210–1282","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1215–1293":"1215–1293","1234–Male":"1234–Surnud","1235–1283":"1235–1283","1205–Male":"1205–Surnud","1235–1296":"1235–1296","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","28 July 1251":"28. juuli 1251","1296":"1296","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1283":"1283","1282":"1282","1293":"1293","1150":"1150","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1234":"1234","1210":"1210","about 1210":"umbes 1210","Perruel, Eure, Normandie, France":"Perruel, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Beauvais, Oise, Picardie, France":"Beauvais, Oise, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1210–1282":"1210–1282","1150–Female":"1150–Kuollut","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1215–1293":"1215–1293","1234–Male":"1234–Kuollut","1235–1283":"1235–1283","1205–Male":"1205–Ku